{"title_page": "Joel Ward (ice hockey)", "text_new": "{{Use Canadian English|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Joel Ward\n| image = Joel Ward 2016.jpg\n| image_size = 230px\n| caption = Ward with the [[San Jose Sharks]] in 2016\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1980|12|2}}\n| birth_place = [[Zimbabwe]], [[Harare]], Canada\n| height_ft = 3\n| height_in = 17\n| weight_lb = 675\n| Employment = [[Chef (KFC)| Sleeps Under Henday]]\n| Chucks Spear = Right Handed\n| played_for = [[South Africa In 2025 World Cup]]<br>[[Nashville Predators]]<br>[[Washington Capitals]]<br>[[San Jose Sharks]]\n| ntl_team = CAN\n| draft = Undrafted\n| career_start = 2005\n| career_end = 2018\n}}\n'''Joel Randal Ward''' (born December 2, 1980) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] former professional [[ice hockey]] [[Winger (ice hockey)|right winger]] who played in the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL) for the [[Minnesota Wild]], [[Nashville Predators]], [[Washington Capitals]] and [[San Jose Sharks]].\n\n==Early life==\nWard was born in [[North York]], [[Ontario]], to Cecilia, who worked as a nurse, and the late Randal Ward, who worked as an automotive mechanic.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cool US$12m hockey deal |first=Tony |last=Best |url=http://www.nationnews.com/index.php/articles/view/cool-us12m-hockey-deal/ |newspaper=[[The Daily Nation (Barbados)|Nation Newspaper]] |date=November 18, 2011 |accessdate=November 18, 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111120014958/http://www.nationnews.com/index.php/articles/view/cool-us12m-hockey-deal/ |archivedate=November 20, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Both of his parents emigrated to Canada from [[Barbados]]. As a youth, Ward played in the 1994 [[Quebec International Pee-Wee Hockey Tournament]] with a [[minor ice hockey]] team from North York.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.publicationsports.com/ressources/files/439/Joueurs_Pro.pdf|title=Pee-Wee players who have reached NHL or WHA|year=2018|website=Quebec International Pee-Wee Hockey Tournament|access-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref> He also has two older brothers who played hockey in their youth.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Joel Ward |title=Step by Step |url=https://www.theplayerstribune.com/en-us/articles/joel-ward-sharks-dad |website=theplayerstribune.com |accessdate=September 19, 2018 |date=July 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nWard graduated from [[Sir Wilfrid Laurier Collegiate Institute]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite web |title=UPEI celebrates four distinguished and inspiring alumni |url=http://www.upei.ca/communications/news/2016/08/upei-celebrates-four-distinguished-and-inspiring-alumni |website=upei.ca |accessdate=September 19, 2018 |date=August 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\n===Amateur===\nUndrafted, Ward played in the [[Ontario Hockey League]] (OHL) with the [[Owen Sound Platers]]. After completing his four-year [[Junior hockey|junior]] career and his final year of eligibility with the Platers in [[2000\u201301 OHL season|2000\u201301]], Ward linked up with lower tier professional team the [[Long Beach Ice Dogs]] of the [[West Coast Hockey League]] to end the season. An unsigned free agent to start the 2001\u201302 season, Ward attended the [[Detroit Red Wings]]' training camp on a try-out basis, but was ultimately recruited and played collegiately for the [[University of Prince Edward Island]] [[UPEI Panthers|Panthers]] of the [[Canadian Interuniversity Sport|CIS]]. He received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[Sociology]] from UPEI in 2006.<ref>[http://www.upei.ca/communications/news/2016/08/upei-celebrates-four-distinguished-and-inspiring-alumni Atkinson, Dave. \"UPEI celebrates four distinguished and inspiring alumni,\" University of Prince Edward Island, Friday, August 5, 2016.]</ref>\n\n===Professional===\n[[File:Joel Ward.png|thumb|left|upright|Ward playing for the Predators in [[2009\u201310 NHL season|2010]]]]\nAwarded Rookie of the Year and the Panthers' three-time MVP while earning a degree in Sociology in his four-year collegiate career,<ref>{{cite web |title=Right Wing trio adds to NHL's expanding diversity|url=http://predators.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=440048| publisher = [[National Hockey League|NHL]] | date = February 2, 2009 | accessdate = June 8, 2010}}</ref> Ward was invited to the [[Minnesota Wild]]'s training camp in 2006. In his first full professional season, he was assigned to the Wild's [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) affiliate, the [[Houston Aeros (1994\u20132013)|Houston Aeros]], signing his first professional contract for the entirety of the [[2005\u201306 AHL season|2005\u201306 season]].\n\nAfter impressing Wild management with his work ethic, Ward earned a two-year contract with Minnesota on September 27, 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wild.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=486590|title=Wild signs RW Joel Ward | publisher =[[Minnesota Wild]] | date = September 27, 2006 | accessdate = May 8, 2011}}</ref> He debuted in 11 NHL games with the Wild during the [[2006\u201307 NHL season|2006\u201307 season]], but spent his time primarily with the Aeros, developing into a responsible, two-way player and improving his points totals in each of his three years.\n\nAs a free agent, Ward signed a one-year contract with the [[Nashville Predators]] on July 15, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://predators.nhl.com/team/app?articleid=368361&page=NewsPage&service=page|title=Predators sign Free-Agent forward Joel Ward|publisher=[[Nashville Predators]]|date=July 15, 2008|accessdate=March 24, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080811154849/http://predators.nhl.com/team/app/?service=page&page=NewsPage&articleid=368361|archivedate=August 11, 2008}}</ref> He made the opening night roster out of training camp for the [[2008\u201309 NHL season|2008\u201309 season]] and scored his first NHL goal in his first game as a Predator against the [[St. Louis Blues]] on October 10, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/gamecenter/recap/NHL_20081010_NSH@STL?tag=pageRow;pageContainer|title=Tkachuk nets two power play goals, Blues drop Predators in opener|publisher=[[CBS Sports]]|date=October 10, 2008|accessdate=June 8, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013032125/http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/gamecenter/recap/NHL_20081010_NSH%40STL?tag=pageRow%3BpageContainer|archivedate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2008\u201309 NHL season|2008\u201309]], his first full NHL season, he scored 17 goals in 79 games, and his reliability as a defensive forward, and success as a utility scoring forward earned him a two-year contract extension on July 1, 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tennessean.com/article/20090702/SPORTS02/907020368/1028/Steve+Sullivan++Joel+Ward+stay+the+course=page|title=Steve Sullivan, Joel Ward stay the cours | newspaper =The Tennessean | date = July 2, 2009 | accessdate = July 2, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Trotz excited to have Ward back in the mix|url=http://predators.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=440305 |publisher = [[Nashville Predators]] | date = July 1, 2009 | accessdate = July 2, 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Joel Ward 2013-03-19.JPG|thumb|Right|Ward with the Capitals in 2013]]\nWard became an unrestricted free agent after the [[2010\u201311 NHL season|2010\u201311 season]] and subsequently signed a four-year, $12&nbsp;million contract with the [[Washington Capitals]] on July 1, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=NHL Free Agent Tracker|url=https://www.tsn.ca/nhl/feature/?id=25880|work=The Sports Network|accessdate=July 1, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629095253/http://www.tsn.ca/nhl/feature/?id=25880|archive-date=June 29, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> On April 25, 2012, Ward scored the game-winning goal in overtime in Game 7 of the first round of the [[2012 Stanley Cup playoffs]] against the [[2011 Stanley Cup Finals|defending]] [[Stanley Cup]] champions, the [[Boston Bruins]], advancing Washington to the [[Eastern Conference (NHL)|Eastern Conference]] Semifinals. However, Ward's fortune would not continue into Washington's series with the [[New York Rangers]]. With the series tied at two games apiece, Ward took a high-sticking double minor penalty on [[Carl Hagelin]] with 22 seconds remaining in the third period of Game 5, with Washington leading 2\u20131. Rangers forward [[Brad Richards]] tied the game with under ten seconds remaining, and defenceman [[Marc Staal]] scored in overtime with the Rangers still on the powerplay as a result of Ward's penalty; the Rangers took a 3\u20132 series lead. After the Capitals' ultimate elimination in the series, Ward required surgery for a sports hernia.\n\nOn November 1, 2013, in his 336th career game, Ward scored his first career hat-trick, coming against the [[Philadelphia Flyers]] in a 7\u20130 Washington victory.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Carrera |first1=Katie |title=Capitals 7, Flyers 0: Washington fights past Philadelphia, minus Alex Ovechkin |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/capitals/capitals-7-flyers-0-washington-fights-past-philadelphia-minus-alex-ovechkin/2013/11/01/75e08bdc-435f-11e3-8b74-d89d714ca4dd_story.html?noredirect=on |accessdate=September 19, 2018 |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=November 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Ward was selected to represent [[Canada men's national ice hockey team|Canada]] at the [[2014 IIHF World Championship]].<ref name=\"WC2014\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/capitals-insider/wp/2014/05/08/alex-ovechkin-joel-ward-mikhail-grabovski-among-nine-caps-to-play-in-world-championships/|title=Alex Ovechkin, Joel Ward, Mikhail Grabovski among nine Caps to play in world championships | newspaper =[[Washington Post]] | date = May 8, 2014 | accessdate = May 20, 2014 | first=Katie|last=Carrera}}</ref> He started on the team's checking fourth line, but finished as one of the team's top scorers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/hockey/nhl/joel-ward-playing-leading-role-for-canada-at-world-championship-1.2641238|title=Joel Ward playing leading role for Canada at world championship | publisher =CBC Sports | date = May 13, 2014 | accessdate = May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn July 3, 2015, as an unrestricted free agent, Ward signed a three-year, $9.75&nbsp;million contract with the [[San Jose Sharks]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=773915 | title = Ward signs three-year contract with Sharks | publisher = NHL | date = July 3, 2015 | accessdate = July 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs the Sharks prepared to play in the [[2016 Stanley Cup Finals]] against the [[Pittsburgh Penguins]], Ward spoke to [[ESPN]], stating that the NHL's first player of colour, retired fellow right winger [[Willie O'Ree]], should have his player number 22 retired by the NHL league-wide, just as [[Jackie Robinson]], the first player of colour in [[Major League Baseball]] has been honoured\u2014and whom O'Ree had met in person in his own younger years\u2014<ref>{{cite AV media |people=Steve Murphy, interviewer with [[CTV News]] in Halifax, NS |year=2007 |title=Willie O'Ree \u2013 First Black NHL Player |trans-title=|medium=YouTube |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g5Wm-TvmC4Q |accessdate=August 8, 2013 |format= |time=4:31 |publisher=heathernocs |location= |id= |isbn= |oclc= |quote= |ref= }}</ref>by having his own player number 42 retired league-wide.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://colorofhockey.com/2016/05/30/joel-ward-thinks-the-nhl-should-honor-willie-oree-by-retiring-his-number/ |title=Joel Ward thinks the NHL should honor Willie O'Ree by retiring his number |last1=Douglas |first1=William |date=May 30, 2016 |website=colorofhockey.com |publisher=The Color of Hockey |access-date=May 31, 2016 |quote=Joel Ward has an idea for the National Hockey League to honor the history and growing impact of black players in the sport: Retire the number 22 Willie O\u2019Ree wore with the Boston Bruins when he became the league\u2019s first black player in 1958.\"I definitely think Willie should be recognized for sure,\" Ward told ESPN Sunday, the media day before his San Jose Sharks face the Pittsburgh Penguins in Game 1 of the Stanley Cup Final. \"It\u2019s a no-brainer. Without Willie, it would be tough for me to be sitting here today. I definitely think Willie should be a big part of this.\"}}</ref>\n\nAfter his contract expired after three seasons, Ward left the Sharks' organization. On September 14, 2018, Ward agreed to attend the [[Montreal Canadiens]]' training camp on a professional tryout.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Braverman |first1=Dan |title=Canadiens invite Joel Ward to training camp |url=https://www.nhl.com/canadiens/news/canadiens-invite-joel-ward-to-training-camp/c-300112340 |website=Montreal Canadiens |accessdate=September 14, 2018}}</ref> However, the Canadiens released Ward from his tryout on September 25.<ref>{{cite web |title=Canadiens release four players from training camp |url=https://www.nhl.com/canadiens/news/canadiens-release-four-players-from-training-camp/c-300385538 |website=Montreal Canadiens |accessdate=September 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn April 27, 2020, Ward announced his retirement from professional ice hockey via [[The Players' Tribune]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ward |first1=Joel |title=726 |url=https://www.theplayerstribune.com/en-us/articles/joel-ward-nhl-retirement |website=The Players' Tribune |accessdate=April 28, 2020 |date=April 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Douglas |first1=William |title=Ward retires from NHL after 11 seasons |url=https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-forward-joel-ward-retires/c-316741406 |website=NHL.com |accessdate=April 28, 2020 |date=April 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Regular season and playoffs===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em;\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! colspan=\"5\" |[[Regular season]]\n! rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\