{"title_page": "Ashura in Morocco", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=May 2014}}\n\nThe '''Day of Ashura''' ({{Lang-ar|\u0639\u0634\u0648\u0631\u0627\u0621}}, meaning the tenth day) in [[Morocco]] has been a traditionally day of celebration and joy. Ashura,sex is celebrated on the tenth day of [[Muharram]] across the Muslim World and is particularly significant for [[Shia Muslims]], where it is a day of mourning. Moroccans however embrace this day with cheerful remembrance of those who have died. It is a custom to pay visit to cemetery pray for the departed ones.\n\nIn [[Morocco]], where the Muslim population is [[Sunni]], the local customs associated with Ashura vary across the country. But traditionally, people exchange mixes of nuts mainly walnuts and almonds, and the popular Dates. Nowadays eclectic variety of Moroccan pastry is added to the mix. Additionally, children are given toys and this is the best time - a week prior to Ashura- to purchase Moroccan traditional musical instruments mainly; ta\u00e2rija drum, Derbouka, Triir and drum tambourines. The night before children play with fireworks in the streets and light bonfire called ''Sh'ala'' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0634\u0639\u0627\u0644\u0629}}). Traditionally females play with vigour the instruments around   this fire reciting traditional Ashura folklore songs. Females then continue to play and sing taking their joy - Nashat- to other neighbours who then join the crowd of players. Marrakech is very known for their Daqqa Marrakchiya performed by Men.\n\nWith the modernisation expansion of cities this custom is becoming more and more rare and can only be seen is some traditional neighbourhoods and small villages.\n\nShia sources allege that these customs may be a legacy of the [[Ummayyad]] rule who sought to time such occasions of popular public display of joy\u2014often pre-existing in local cultures\u2014with the Ashura day in order to humiliate and counter the mourning of their enemies, the supporters of [[Ali]] (Shi'a).<ref name=shia>{{cite web|title=\u0634\u0628\u0643\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u064a\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0644\u0645\u064a\u0629 - \u0641\u0631\u062d \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0648\u0627\u0635\u0628 \u0623\u0639\u062f\u0627\u0621 \u0622\u0644 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f (\u0635) \u0641\u064a \u064a\u0648\u0645 \u0639\u0627\u0634\u0648\u0631\u0627\u0621|url=http://www.shiaweb.org/v2/news/article_61.html|accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref> The latter see this day as a great catastrophe since it was the day of the death of [[Husayn ibn Ali|Hussein]] and the slaughtering of his family at the [[battle of Karbala]]. However, today in Morocco, the event is not at all associated with the Shia-Sunni conflict and has little religious significance and is seen as merely a folk tradition.\n\n==The Light of Baba Ashur==\nIn some regions of Morocco, the right of ur is an activity for children during the festival of Ashura, wherein children wander from one house to another asking for candy and dried fruits or even money and asking the question \"the right of Baba Aichore?\" of anyone who answers the door   This tradition has become famous recently when it has been considered as a substitute for fireworks which usually lead to a range of accidents.\n\n==City customs==\n\nIn some cities, Moroccans call the tenth day of Muharram, [[Zamzam Well|Zamzam]] day. On this day, they spray water on each other. Whoever wakes up first sprays the rest with cold water, and gets lots of children and young people out (especially in the popular neighbourhoods) into the streets to spray every passerby with of water. Over the course of the first hours of the morning there are fierce \"water battles,\" especially among friends and neighbors. Whoever refuses to celebrate with \"Zamzam water,\" by  sprinkling a little of it on his clothes, may be exposed to a number of volunteers taking turns dumping all of their water on his clothes. Then the day is capped off with a meal of \"Moroccan couscous\" with dried meat - La Khloua'- saved especially for this day  from the sacrifice of Eid al-Adha.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Moroccan culture]]\n[[Category:Islamic culture]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=May 2014}}\n\nThe '''Day of Ashura''' ({{Lang-ar|\u0639\u0634\u0648\u0631\u0627\u0621}}, meaning the tenth day) in [[Morocco]] has been a traditionally day of celebration and joy. Ashura, which is celebrated on the tenth day of [[Muharram]] across the Muslim World and is particularly significant for [[Shia Muslims]], where it is a day of mourning. Moroccans however embrace this day with cheerful remembrance of those who have died. It is a custom to pay visit to cemetery pray for the departed ones.\n\nIn [[Morocco]], where the Muslim population is [[Sunni]], the local customs associated with Ashura vary across the country. But traditionally, people exchange mixes of nuts mainly walnuts and almonds, and the popular Dates. Nowadays eclectic variety of Moroccan pastry is added to the mix. Additionally, children are given toys and this is the best time - a week prior to Ashura- to purchase Moroccan traditional musical instruments mainly; ta\u00e2rija drum, Derbouka, Triir and drum tambourines. The night before children play with fireworks in the streets and light bonfire called ''Sh'ala'' ({{lang-ar|\u0627\u0644\u0634\u0639\u0627\u0644\u0629}}). Traditionally females play with vigour the instruments around   this fire reciting traditional Ashura folklore songs. Females then continue to play and sing taking their joy - Nashat- to other neighbours who then join the crowd of players. Marrakech is very known for their Daqqa Marrakchiya performed by Men.\n\nWith the modernisation expansion of cities this custom is becoming more and more rare and can only be seen is some traditional neighbourhoods and small villages.\n\nShia sources allege that these customs may be a legacy of the [[Ummayyad]] rule who sought to time such occasions of popular public display of joy\u2014often pre-existing in local cultures\u2014with the Ashura day in order to humiliate and counter the mourning of their enemies, the supporters of [[Ali]] (Shi'a).<ref name=shia>{{cite web|title=\u0634\u0628\u0643\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0634\u064a\u0639\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0644\u0645\u064a\u0629 - \u0641\u0631\u062d \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0648\u0627\u0635\u0628 \u0623\u0639\u062f\u0627\u0621 \u0622\u0644 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f (\u0635) \u0641\u064a \u064a\u0648\u0645 \u0639\u0627\u0634\u0648\u0631\u0627\u0621|url=http://www.shiaweb.org/v2/news/article_61.html|accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref> The latter see this day as a great catastrophe since it was the day of the death of [[Husayn ibn Ali|Hussein]] and the slaughtering of his family at the [[battle of Karbala]]. However, today in Morocco, the event is not at all associated with the Shia-Sunni conflict and has little religious significance and is seen as merely a folk tradition.\n\n==The Light of Baba Ashur==\nIn some regions of Morocco, the right of ur is an activity for children during the festival of Ashura, wherein children wander from one house to another asking for candy and dried fruits or even money and asking the question \"the right of Baba Aichore?\" of anyone who answers the door   This tradition has become famous recently when it has been considered as a substitute for fireworks which usually lead to a range of accidents.\n\n==City customs==\n\nIn some cities, Moroccans call the tenth day of Muharram, [[Zamzam Well|Zamzam]] day. On this day, they spray water on each other. Whoever wakes up first sprays the rest with cold water, and gets lots of children and young people out (especially in the popular neighbourhoods) into the streets to spray every passerby with of water. Over the course of the first hours of the morning there are fierce \"water battles,\" especially among friends and neighbors. Whoever refuses to celebrate with \"Zamzam water,\" by  sprinkling a little of it on his clothes, may be exposed to a number of volunteers taking turns dumping all of their water on his clothes. Then the day is capped off with a meal of \"Moroccan couscous\" with dried meat - La Khloua'- saved especially for this day  from the sacrifice of Eid al-Adha.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Moroccan culture]]\n[[Category:Islamic culture]]\n", "name_user": "2001:14bb:80:aa7:f862:e5:a9b3:da55", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Ggexh)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ashura_in_Morocco"}
{"title_page": "Boney Kapoor", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian film producer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Boney Kapoor\n| image              = Boney Kapoor (10) (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Kapoor in 2012\n| birth_name         = Achal Kapoor\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1955|11|11|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Here's How Arjun, Janhvi, Khushi and Anshula Made Boney Kapoor's 63rd Birthday Special |url=https://www.news18.com/news/movies/arjun-janhvi-and-kapoor-clan-unite-to-celebrate-boney-kapoors-birthday-see-post-1935635.html |accessdate=29 September 2019 |work=News18 |date=11 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Boney Kapoor celebrates birthday with Janhvi, Khushi and Arjun. See pics |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/celebrities/story/boney-kapoor-celebrates-birthday-with-janhvi-khushi-and-arjun-see-pics-1386053-2018-11-11 |accessdate=29 September 2019 |work=India Today |date=11 November 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Meerut]], [[uttar Pradesh State]], [[India]]\n| nationality        = [[Indian people|Indian]]\n| occupation         = Film producer \n| years active       = 1980 - Present\n| spouse             = {{ublist| {{married|[[Mona Shourie Kapoor]]|1983|1996|end=div.}}|{{married|[[Sridevi]]|1996|2018|end=d.}}<ref name=\"ABC_2018-02-24\">{{cite news |title=Sridevi, Bollywood leading lady of '80s and '90s, dies at 54 |date=24 February 2018 |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory/sridevi-bollywood-leading-lady-80s-90s-dies-54-53337091 |work=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=24 February 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225050841/http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory/sridevi-bollywood-leading-lady-80s-90s-dies-54-53337091 |archivedate=25 February 2018 }}</ref> }}\n| children           = 4 (including [[Arjun Kapoor]] and [[Janhvi Kapoor]])\n| parents            = [[Surinder Kapoor]]<br/>Nirmal Kapoor\n| relatives          = See [[List of Hindi film families#Kapoor family (of Surinder Kapoor)|Surinder Kapoor family]] and [[Kapoor family]]\n}}\n\n'''Boney Kapoor''' (born '''Achal Kapoor'''; 11 November 1955) is an [[Indian people|Indian]] film producer who has produced numerous [[Bollywood]] films like ''[[Mr. India (1987 film)|Mr. India]]'', ''[[No Entry]]'', ''[[Judaai (1997 film)|Judaai]]'' and ''[[Wanted (2009 film)|Wanted]]'' to his credit. He was married to actress [[Sridevi]] until her death in 2018. He is the elder brother of actors [[Anil Kapoor]] and [[Sanjay Kapoor]] and father of film actors [[Arjun Kapoor]] and [[Janhvi Kapoor]].\n\n==Personal life==\nBoney Kapoor was born in 1953, the son of the late [[Surinder Kapoor]] who was a Bollywood film producer. His brothers ([[Anil Kapoor|Anil]] and [[Sanjay Kapoor|Sanjay]]) are actors and producers.\n\nKapoor was married to [[Mona Shourie Kapoor|Mona Shourie]] in 1983 and the couple have two children, [[Arjun Kapoor]] (born 1985) and Anshula (born in 1990). Arjun made his acting debut in the 2012 movie ''[[Ishaqzaade]]'' while Anshula graduated from [[Barnard College]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Mumbai Mirror |url=http://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/International-affairs-City-that-never-sleeps/articleshow/54773146.cms |website=MumbaiMirror |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161213160559/http://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/International-affairs-City-that-never-sleeps/articleshow/54773146.cms |archivedate=13 December 2016 }}</ref>\n\nBoney married Indian actress [[Sridevi]] on 2 June 1996. The couple had two daughters, Janhvi Kapoor (born 6 March 1997) and Khushi (born 5 November 2000).<ref>{{Cite web |title=rediff.com, Movies: Showbuzz! Boney, Sridevi's daughter called Khushi |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2000/nov/30sri.htm |website=www.rediff.com |accessdate=19 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304125723/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2000/nov/30sri.htm |archivedate=4 March 2016 }}</ref> On 24 February 2018, Sridevi died<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://dehubs.com/news/bollywood-actress-sridevi-passes-away-age-54/ |title=Bollywood actress Sridevi passes away at the age of 54 |date=25 February 2018 |work=Dehubs |access-date=24 February 2018 |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225105404/https://dehubs.com/news/bollywood-actress-sridevi-passes-away-age-54/ |archive-date=25 February 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> in Dubai after drowning in her hotel bath tub.\n\n==Career as producer==\n\nBoney Kapoor started his career working under legends like [[Shakti Samanta]]. The most famous film produced by him remains the [[Shekhar Kapur]] directed sci-fi film ''[[Mr. India (1987 film)|Mr India]]'' starring [[Anil Kapoor]] and [[Sridevi]]. It was the second biggest hit of 1987 and remains a cult classic in India. The film was known for several of its lines and songs, including Sridevi's \"Miss Hawa Hawaii\" performance and [[Amrish Puri]]'s quote \"Mogambo khush hua\" (Mogambo is pleased), which is one of the most famous quotes of Bollywood and has become synonymous with Puri.<ref name=top>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oneknightstands.net/top-20-villains-of-bollywood/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170618071628/http://www.oneknightstands.net/top-20-villains-of-bollywood/|url-status=dead|title=Top 20 Villains of Bollywood|date=16 December 2008|archivedate=18 June 2017}}</ref> The Mogambo character is considered to be one of the best villains in Bollywood history.<ref name=top/>\n\n[[Laxmikant-Pyarelal]]'s music performed well too, especially the song \"Hawa Hawaii\" which is very popular till today. ''[[Mr. India (1987 film)|Mr India]]'' has often been featured in lists of top Bollywood films. ''[[Indiatimes|Indiatimes Movies]]'' ranks the movie amongst the Top 25 Must See Bollywood Films.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Kanwar, Rachna |title=25 Must See Bollywood Movies |date=3 October 2005 |url=http://movies.indiatimes.com/Special_Features/25_Must_See_Bollywood_Movies/articleshow/msid-1250837,curpg-6.cms |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120717044058/http://movies.indiatimes.com/Special_Features/25_Must_See_Bollywood_Movies/articleshow/msid-1250837,curpg-6.cms |url-status=dead |archive-date=17 July 2012 |publisher=Indiatimes movies |accessdate=8 November 2010}}</ref> This was the last film that the duo Salim-Javed wrote together. They had split up earlier in 1982, but came back for one last film. It was remade in [[Tamil cinema|Tamil]] as ''En Rathathin Rathame'', starring [[K. Bhagyaraj]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140305110619/http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/57137.html Kollywood: Ms. Indias and Ms. Worlds \u2013 I], IndiaGlitz. 20 May 2010</ref> in [[Kannada]] as ''Jai Karnataka'', starring [[Ambareesh]]. On the centenary of Indian cinema, ''Mr. India'' has been declared one of the 100 Greatest Indian Films of All Time.<ref>{{cite web |last=ibnlive |title=100 Years of Indian Cinema: The 100 greatest Indian films of all time |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/photogallery/13200-7.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130425234939/http://ibnlive.in.com/photogallery/13200-7.html |archivedate=25 April 2013 }}</ref> Described by [[Rediff]] as \"one of the most iconic films of its time\",<ref name=\"http\">{{cite web |last=Rediff |title=PIX: The Changing Faces of Sridevi |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-pix-the-changing-faces-of-sridevi/20121009.htm |date=9 October 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115061354/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-pix-the-changing-faces-of-sridevi/20121009.htm |archivedate=15 January 2013 }}</ref> it became one of the highest grossing hits of 1987.<ref>{{cite web |last=Boxofficeindia.com |title=Box Office 1987 |url=http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=193&catName=MTk4Nw== |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090201143818/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=193&catName=MTk4Nw%3D%3D |archivedate=1 February 2009 }}</ref> and also found a place in [[Hindustan Times]] list of 'Top 10 Patriotic Films of Hindi Cinema'.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hindustan Times |title=Top 10 Patriotic Films |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/photos-news/Photos-Entertainment/toptenpatrioticmovies/Article4.aspx |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130809064003/http://www.hindustantimes.com/photos-news/Photos-Entertainment/toptenpatrioticmovies/Article4.aspx |archivedate=9 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nHis other early productions include ''[[Hum Paanch (1980 film)|Hum Paanch]]'' which played a key role in establishing actors like [[Mithun Chakraborty]] and [[Amrish Puri]] in Bollywood. Boney Kapoor also launched many big stars of the Hindi film industry. His production ''[[Woh Saat Din]]'' launched brother [[Anil Kapoor]], ''Prem'' launched younger brother [[Sanjay Kapoor]] and [[Tabu (actress)|Tabu]], and ''[[Koi Mere Dil Se Poochhe]]'' launched actress [[Esha Deol]]. He is considered one of the most lavish producers of Bollywood who produced one of the most expensive films in the history of Hindi cinema: ''[[Roop Ki Rani Choron Ka Raja (1993 film)|Roop Ki Rani Choron Ka Raja]]'' in 1993. In 1997, he produced the box office hit ''[[Judaai (1997 film)|Judaai]]'' starring [[Sridevi]], [[Anil Kapoor]] and [[Urmila Matondkar]].\n\nBoney Kapoor was managing Anil's career well until 1999 and in 2000 he produced ''[[Pukar (2000 film)|Pukar]]'' starring [[Anil Kapoor]], [[Madhuri Dixit]], [[Namrata Shirodkar]], [[Danny Denzongpa]] and [[Om Puri]]. The film was critically acclaimed and a moderate success at the box office.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071218132345/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/2000.htm Box office 2000]. boxofficeindia.com</ref> It won two [[National Film Awards]], including the [[Nargis Dutt Award for Best Feature Film on National Integration]] and the [[National Film Award for Best Actor]] for Anil Kapoor's performance.\n\nIn 2002, he produced ''Company'' directed by [[Ram Gopal Varma]] starring [[Ajay Devgan]], [[Mohanlal]], [[Manisha Koirala]], [[Vivek Oberoi]], and [[Antara Mali]]. It is a fictional expos\u00e9 of the [[Mumbai]] underworld, loosely based on the [[Indian mafia]] organisation [[D-Company]], known to be run by [[Dawood Ibrahim]]. The film received positive reviews from critics as well as audience and won six out of the eleven awards it was nominated for at the [[Filmfare Awards]]. The film received critical acclaim at the 2004 [[Austin Film Festival]] and [[New York Asian Film Festival]].<ref name=David>{{cite web |author=David |title=The Films of Ram Gopal Varma \u2013 An Overview |publisher=Cinema Strikes Back |date=16 June 2006 |url=http://www.cinemastrikesback.com/?p=1202 |accessdate=22 February 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090725153007/http://www.cinemastrikesback.com/?p=1202 |archivedate=25 July 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIt is the second film in the [[Gangster (film series)|''Gangster'' series]] and a sequel to the film ''[[Satya]]''. It was followed by a sequel, ''[[D (film)|D]]''.\nFilm critic Rajeev Masand has labelled it (along with its prequel ''[[Satya (1998 film)|Satya]]'') one of the \"most influential movies of the past ten years.\"<ref name=\"masand-contract-verdict\">{{cite news |title=Masand's Verdict: Contract, mangled mess of Satya, Company |author=Rajeev Masand |work=CNN-IBN |date=18 July 2008 |accessdate=18 August 2010 |url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/masands-verdict-contract-mangled-mess-of-satya-company/69135-8.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202220525/http://www.ibnlive.com/news/masands-verdict-contract-mangled-mess-of-satya-company/69135-8.html |archivedate=2 December 2008 }}</ref> ''Company'' marked the introduction of a new genre of film making, a variation of film noir<ref name=\"dwyer\">{{cite news |title=Behind The Scenes |author=Rachel Dwyer |work=Outlook Magazine |date=30 May 2005 |accessdate=18 August 2010 |url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?227527}}</ref> that has been called ''Mumbai noir'', of which he is the acknowledged master.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bollywood on the table |author=Aruti Nayar |work=The Tribune |date=16 December 2007 |accessdate=19 June 2008 |url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2007/20071216/spectrum/main11.htm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AC5SK6Up?url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2007/20071216/spectrum/main11.htm |archivedate=26 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\nHis 2004 film ''[[Run (2004 film)|Run]]'' starring [[Abhishek Bachchan]] was a box office failure.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://boxofficeindia.com/Star_Cast/actor_detail/abhishek_bachchan |title=Abhishek Bachchan box office |work=Box OfficeIndia |accessdate=7 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150918183004/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/Star_Cast/actor_detail/abhishek_bachchan |archivedate=18 September 2015 }}</ref> Following this the comedy ''[[No Entry]]'' produced by him became Bollywood's biggest hit of 2005. It gained a lot of popularity grossing Rs. {{formatnum:430000000}}.<ref>{{cite web |title=Box Office 2005 |url=http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=211&catName=MjAwNQ== |publisher=Boxofficeindia.com |accessdate=13 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111130532/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=211 |archivedate=11 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Boney Kapoor produced ''[[Wanted (2009 film)|Wanted]]'' starring [[Salman Khan]]. The film broke many records at the box office upon release, due to Khan's comeback. ''[[Wanted (2009 film)|Wanted]]'' was the second highest-grossing Bollywood film of 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/news-interviews/Bollywood-is-Tollywoods-fan/articleshow/10088678.cms |title=Bollywood is Tollywood's fan |work=Times of India |accessdate=26 September 2011 |date=23 September 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150820064311/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/news-interviews/Bollywood-is-Tollywoods-fan/articleshow/10088678.cms |archivedate=20 August 2015 }}</ref> It had an excellent opening, grossing Rs. 440&nbsp;million in the first week.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.qatar-tribune.com/data/20090929/pdf/chillout.pdf |title=Qatar Tribune |accessdate=17 August 2010}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> It shattered records in Pakistan, grossing over Rs. 1750&nbsp;million in its first weekend, which was a record for any Indian film.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/salmans-wanted-collects-75-mn-in-pak/102252-8.html |title=Salman's Wanted collects 7.5 m in Pakistan |author=Johnny Vaz |date=26 September 2009 |work=IBN |accessdate=26 February 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131009020600/http://ibnlive.in.com/news/salmans-wanted-collects-75-mn-in-pak/102252-8.html |archivedate=9 October 2013 }}</ref> It grossed Rs. 1012.5&nbsp;million in India and Rs. 260.6&nbsp;million overseas.<ref>{{cite web |title=Top Lifetime Grossers Worldwide (IND Rs) |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=312&catName=TGlmZXRpbWU= |publisher=Boxofficeindia.com |accessdate=28 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708090124/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=312&catName=TGlmZXRpbWU%3D |archivedate=8 July 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Box Office 2009 |url=http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=288&catName=MjAwOQ== |publisher=Boxofficeindia.com |accessdate=28 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210202343/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=288&catName=MjAwOQ%3D%3D |archivedate=10 February 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"weeklyvoice1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.weeklyvoice.com/~epaper/00pdfs/20100102v.pdf |title=The Weekly Voice |accessdate=17 August 2010}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Film\n|-\n|1980\n|''[[Hum Paanch (1980 film)|Hum Paanch]]''\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[Woh Saat Din]]''\n|-\n|1987\n|''[[Mr. India (1987 film)|Mr. India]]''\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Raat (film)|Raat]]''\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Drohi (1992 film)|Drohi]]''\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Roop Ki Rani Choron Ka Raja (1993 film)|Roop Ki Rani Choron Ka Raja]]''\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Prem (film)|Prem]]''\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Loafer (1996 film)|Loafer]]''\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Judaai (1997 film)|Judaai]]''\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Sirf Tum]]''\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[Pukar (2000 film)|Pukar]]''\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[Hamara Dil Aapke Paas Hai]]''\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Koi Mere Dil Se Poochhe]]''\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Company (film)|Company]]''\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Shakti (2002 film)|Shakti]]''\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[Khushi (2003 Hindi film)|Khushi]]''\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Run (2004 film)|Run]]''\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Kyun...! Ho Gaya Na]]''\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Bewafaa (2005 film)|Bewafaa]]''\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[No Entry]]''\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Wanted (2009 film)|Wanted]]''\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Milenge Milenge]]''\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Tevar (film)|Tevar]]''\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Mom (film)|Mom]]''\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Nerkonda Paarvai]]'' (Tamil)\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Maidaan]]''\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Valimai]]'' (Tamil)\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Vakeel Saab]]'' (Telugu)\n|-\n|''TBA''\n|''[[Badhaai Ho]] [[remake]]''\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|438470|Boney Kapoor}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kapoor, Boney}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Hindi film producers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian film producer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Boney Kapoor\n| image              = Boney Kapoor (10) (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Kapoor in 2012\n| birth_name         = Achal Kapoor\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1955|11|11|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite news |title=Here's How Arjun, Janhvi, Khushi and Anshula Made Boney Kapoor's 63rd Birthday Special |url=https://www.news18.com/news/movies/arjun-janhvi-and-kapoor-clan-unite-to-celebrate-boney-kapoors-birthday-see-post-1935635.html |accessdate=29 September 2019 |work=News18 |date=11 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Boney Kapoor celebrates birthday with Janhvi, Khushi and Arjun. See pics |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/celebrities/story/boney-kapoor-celebrates-birthday-with-janhvi-khushi-and-arjun-see-pics-1386053-2018-11-11 |accessdate=29 September 2019 |work=India Today |date=11 November 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Bombay]], [[Bombay State]], [[India]]\n| nationality        = [[Indian people|Indian]]\n| occupation         = Film producer \n| years active       = 1980 - Present\n| spouse             = {{ublist| {{married|[[Mona Shourie Kapoor]]|1983|1996|end=div.}}|{{married|[[Sridevi]]|1996|2018|end=d.}}<ref name=\"ABC_2018-02-24\">{{cite news |title=Sridevi, Bollywood leading lady of '80s and '90s, dies at 54 |date=24 February 2018 |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory/sridevi-bollywood-leading-lady-80s-90s-dies-54-53337091 |work=[[Associated Press]] |access-date=24 February 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225050841/http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory/sridevi-bollywood-leading-lady-80s-90s-dies-54-53337091 |archivedate=25 February 2018 }}</ref> }}\n| children           = 4 (including [[Arjun Kapoor]] and [[Janhvi Kapoor]])\n| parents            = [[Surinder Kapoor]]<br/>Nirmal Kapoor\n| relatives          = See [[List of Hindi film families#Kapoor family (of Surinder Kapoor)|Surinder Kapoor family]] and [[Kapoor family]]\n}}\n\n'''Boney Kapoor''' (born '''Achal Kapoor'''; 11 November 1955) is an [[Indian people|Indian]] film producer who has produced numerous [[Bollywood]] films like ''[[Mr. India (1987 film)|Mr. India]]'', ''[[No Entry]]'', ''[[Judaai (1997 film)|Judaai]]'' and ''[[Wanted (2009 film)|Wanted]]'' to his credit. He was married to actress [[Sridevi]] until her death in 2018. He is the elder brother of actors [[Anil Kapoor]] and [[Sanjay Kapoor]] and father of film actors [[Arjun Kapoor]] and [[Janhvi Kapoor]].\n\n==Personal life==\nBoney Kapoor was born in 1953, the son of the late [[Surinder Kapoor]] who was a Bollywood film producer. His brothers ([[Anil Kapoor|Anil]] and [[Sanjay Kapoor|Sanjay]]) are actors and producers.\n\nKapoor was married to [[Mona Shourie Kapoor|Mona Shourie]] in 1983 and the couple have two children, [[Arjun Kapoor]] (born 1985) and Anshula (born in 1990). Arjun made his acting debut in the 2012 movie ''[[Ishaqzaade]]'' while Anshula graduated from [[Barnard College]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Mumbai Mirror |url=http://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/International-affairs-City-that-never-sleeps/articleshow/54773146.cms |website=MumbaiMirror |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161213160559/http://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/International-affairs-City-that-never-sleeps/articleshow/54773146.cms |archivedate=13 December 2016 }}</ref>\n\nBoney married Indian actress [[Sridevi]] on 2 June 1996. The couple had two daughters, Janhvi Kapoor (born 6 March 1997) and Khushi (born 5 November 2000).<ref>{{Cite web |title=rediff.com, Movies: Showbuzz! Boney, Sridevi's daughter called Khushi |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2000/nov/30sri.htm |website=www.rediff.com |accessdate=19 September 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304125723/http://www.rediff.com/movies/2000/nov/30sri.htm |archivedate=4 March 2016 }}</ref> On 24 February 2018, Sridevi died<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://dehubs.com/news/bollywood-actress-sridevi-passes-away-age-54/ |title=Bollywood actress Sridevi passes away at the age of 54 |date=25 February 2018 |work=Dehubs |access-date=24 February 2018 |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180225105404/https://dehubs.com/news/bollywood-actress-sridevi-passes-away-age-54/ |archive-date=25 February 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> in Dubai after drowning in her hotel bath tub.\n\n==Career as producer==\n\nBoney Kapoor started his career working under legends like [[Shakti Samanta]]. The most famous film produced by him remains the [[Shekhar Kapur]] directed sci-fi film ''[[Mr. India (1987 film)|Mr India]]'' starring [[Anil Kapoor]] and [[Sridevi]]. It was the second biggest hit of 1987 and remains a cult classic in India. The film was known for several of its lines and songs, including Sridevi's \"Miss Hawa Hawaii\" performance and [[Amrish Puri]]'s quote \"Mogambo khush hua\" (Mogambo is pleased), which is one of the most famous quotes of Bollywood and has become synonymous with Puri.<ref name=top>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oneknightstands.net/top-20-villains-of-bollywood/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170618071628/http://www.oneknightstands.net/top-20-villains-of-bollywood/|url-status=dead|title=Top 20 Villains of Bollywood|date=16 December 2008|archivedate=18 June 2017}}</ref> The Mogambo character is considered to be one of the best villains in Bollywood history.<ref name=top/>\n\n[[Laxmikant-Pyarelal]]'s music performed well too, especially the song \"Hawa Hawaii\" which is very popular till today. ''[[Mr. India (1987 film)|Mr India]]'' has often been featured in lists of top Bollywood films. ''[[Indiatimes|Indiatimes Movies]]'' ranks the movie amongst the Top 25 Must See Bollywood Films.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Kanwar, Rachna |title=25 Must See Bollywood Movies |date=3 October 2005 |url=http://movies.indiatimes.com/Special_Features/25_Must_See_Bollywood_Movies/articleshow/msid-1250837,curpg-6.cms |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120717044058/http://movies.indiatimes.com/Special_Features/25_Must_See_Bollywood_Movies/articleshow/msid-1250837,curpg-6.cms |url-status=dead |archive-date=17 July 2012 |publisher=Indiatimes movies |accessdate=8 November 2010}}</ref> This was the last film that the duo Salim-Javed wrote together. They had split up earlier in 1982, but came back for one last film. It was remade in [[Tamil cinema|Tamil]] as ''En Rathathin Rathame'', starring [[K. Bhagyaraj]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140305110619/http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/57137.html Kollywood: Ms. Indias and Ms. Worlds \u2013 I], IndiaGlitz. 20 May 2010</ref> in [[Kannada]] as ''Jai Karnataka'', starring [[Ambareesh]]. On the centenary of Indian cinema, ''Mr. India'' has been declared one of the 100 Greatest Indian Films of All Time.<ref>{{cite web |last=ibnlive |title=100 Years of Indian Cinema: The 100 greatest Indian films of all time |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/photogallery/13200-7.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130425234939/http://ibnlive.in.com/photogallery/13200-7.html |archivedate=25 April 2013 }}</ref> Described by [[Rediff]] as \"one of the most iconic films of its time\",<ref name=\"http\">{{cite web |last=Rediff |title=PIX: The Changing Faces of Sridevi |url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-pix-the-changing-faces-of-sridevi/20121009.htm |date=9 October 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115061354/http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-pix-the-changing-faces-of-sridevi/20121009.htm |archivedate=15 January 2013 }}</ref> it became one of the highest grossing hits of 1987.<ref>{{cite web |last=Boxofficeindia.com |title=Box Office 1987 |url=http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=193&catName=MTk4Nw== |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090201143818/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=193&catName=MTk4Nw%3D%3D |archivedate=1 February 2009 }}</ref> and also found a place in [[Hindustan Times]] list of 'Top 10 Patriotic Films of Hindi Cinema'.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hindustan Times |title=Top 10 Patriotic Films |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/photos-news/Photos-Entertainment/toptenpatrioticmovies/Article4.aspx |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130809064003/http://www.hindustantimes.com/photos-news/Photos-Entertainment/toptenpatrioticmovies/Article4.aspx |archivedate=9 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nHis other early productions include ''[[Hum Paanch (1980 film)|Hum Paanch]]'' which played a key role in establishing actors like [[Mithun Chakraborty]] and [[Amrish Puri]] in Bollywood. Boney Kapoor also launched many big stars of the Hindi film industry. His production ''[[Woh Saat Din]]'' launched brother [[Anil Kapoor]], ''Prem'' launched younger brother [[Sanjay Kapoor]] and [[Tabu (actress)|Tabu]], and ''[[Koi Mere Dil Se Poochhe]]'' launched actress [[Esha Deol]]. He is considered one of the most lavish producers of Bollywood who produced one of the most expensive films in the history of Hindi cinema: ''[[Roop Ki Rani Choron Ka Raja (1993 film)|Roop Ki Rani Choron Ka Raja]]'' in 1993. In 1997, he produced the box office hit ''[[Judaai (1997 film)|Judaai]]'' starring [[Sridevi]], [[Anil Kapoor]] and [[Urmila Matondkar]].\n\nBoney Kapoor was managing Anil's career well until 1999 and in 2000 he produced ''[[Pukar (2000 film)|Pukar]]'' starring [[Anil Kapoor]], [[Madhuri Dixit]], [[Namrata Shirodkar]], [[Danny Denzongpa]] and [[Om Puri]]. The film was critically acclaimed and a moderate success at the box office.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071218132345/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/2000.htm Box office 2000]. boxofficeindia.com</ref> It won two [[National Film Awards]], including the [[Nargis Dutt Award for Best Feature Film on National Integration]] and the [[National Film Award for Best Actor]] for Anil Kapoor's performance.\n\nIn 2002, he produced ''Company'' directed by [[Ram Gopal Varma]] starring [[Ajay Devgan]], [[Mohanlal]], [[Manisha Koirala]], [[Vivek Oberoi]], and [[Antara Mali]]. It is a fictional expos\u00e9 of the [[Mumbai]] underworld, loosely based on the [[Indian mafia]] organisation [[D-Company]], known to be run by [[Dawood Ibrahim]]. The film received positive reviews from critics as well as audience and won six out of the eleven awards it was nominated for at the [[Filmfare Awards]]. The film received critical acclaim at the 2004 [[Austin Film Festival]] and [[New York Asian Film Festival]].<ref name=David>{{cite web |author=David |title=The Films of Ram Gopal Varma \u2013 An Overview |publisher=Cinema Strikes Back |date=16 June 2006 |url=http://www.cinemastrikesback.com/?p=1202 |accessdate=22 February 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090725153007/http://www.cinemastrikesback.com/?p=1202 |archivedate=25 July 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIt is the second film in the [[Gangster (film series)|''Gangster'' series]] and a sequel to the film ''[[Satya]]''. It was followed by a sequel, ''[[D (film)|D]]''.\nFilm critic Rajeev Masand has labelled it (along with its prequel ''[[Satya (1998 film)|Satya]]'') one of the \"most influential movies of the past ten years.\"<ref name=\"masand-contract-verdict\">{{cite news |title=Masand's Verdict: Contract, mangled mess of Satya, Company |author=Rajeev Masand |work=CNN-IBN |date=18 July 2008 |accessdate=18 August 2010 |url=http://www.ibnlive.com/news/masands-verdict-contract-mangled-mess-of-satya-company/69135-8.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202220525/http://www.ibnlive.com/news/masands-verdict-contract-mangled-mess-of-satya-company/69135-8.html |archivedate=2 December 2008 }}</ref> ''Company'' marked the introduction of a new genre of film making, a variation of film noir<ref name=\"dwyer\">{{cite news |title=Behind The Scenes |author=Rachel Dwyer |work=Outlook Magazine |date=30 May 2005 |accessdate=18 August 2010 |url=http://www.outlookindia.com/article.aspx?227527}}</ref> that has been called ''Mumbai noir'', of which he is the acknowledged master.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bollywood on the table |author=Aruti Nayar |work=The Tribune |date=16 December 2007 |accessdate=19 June 2008 |url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2007/20071216/spectrum/main11.htm |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6AC5SK6Up?url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/2007/20071216/spectrum/main11.htm |archivedate=26 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\nHis 2004 film ''[[Run (2004 film)|Run]]'' starring [[Abhishek Bachchan]] was a box office failure.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://boxofficeindia.com/Star_Cast/actor_detail/abhishek_bachchan |title=Abhishek Bachchan box office |work=Box OfficeIndia |accessdate=7 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150918183004/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/Star_Cast/actor_detail/abhishek_bachchan |archivedate=18 September 2015 }}</ref> Following this the comedy ''[[No Entry]]'' produced by him became Bollywood's biggest hit of 2005. It gained a lot of popularity grossing Rs. {{formatnum:430000000}}.<ref>{{cite web |title=Box Office 2005 |url=http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=211&catName=MjAwNQ== |publisher=Boxofficeindia.com |accessdate=13 August 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111130532/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=211 |archivedate=11 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Boney Kapoor produced ''[[Wanted (2009 film)|Wanted]]'' starring [[Salman Khan]]. The film broke many records at the box office upon release, due to Khan's comeback. ''[[Wanted (2009 film)|Wanted]]'' was the second highest-grossing Bollywood film of 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/news-interviews/Bollywood-is-Tollywoods-fan/articleshow/10088678.cms |title=Bollywood is Tollywood's fan |work=Times of India |accessdate=26 September 2011 |date=23 September 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150820064311/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/news-interviews/Bollywood-is-Tollywoods-fan/articleshow/10088678.cms |archivedate=20 August 2015 }}</ref> It had an excellent opening, grossing Rs. 440&nbsp;million in the first week.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.qatar-tribune.com/data/20090929/pdf/chillout.pdf |title=Qatar Tribune |accessdate=17 August 2010}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> It shattered records in Pakistan, grossing over Rs. 1750&nbsp;million in its first weekend, which was a record for any Indian film.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/salmans-wanted-collects-75-mn-in-pak/102252-8.html |title=Salman's Wanted collects 7.5 m in Pakistan |author=Johnny Vaz |date=26 September 2009 |work=IBN |accessdate=26 February 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131009020600/http://ibnlive.in.com/news/salmans-wanted-collects-75-mn-in-pak/102252-8.html |archivedate=9 October 2013 }}</ref> It grossed Rs. 1012.5&nbsp;million in India and Rs. 260.6&nbsp;million overseas.<ref>{{cite web |title=Top Lifetime Grossers Worldwide (IND Rs) |url=http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=312&catName=TGlmZXRpbWU= |publisher=Boxofficeindia.com |accessdate=28 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708090124/http://www.boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=312&catName=TGlmZXRpbWU%3D |archivedate=8 July 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Box Office 2009 |url=http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=288&catName=MjAwOQ== |publisher=Boxofficeindia.com |accessdate=28 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210202343/http://boxofficeindia.com/showProd.php?itemCat=288&catName=MjAwOQ%3D%3D |archivedate=10 February 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"weeklyvoice1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.weeklyvoice.com/~epaper/00pdfs/20100102v.pdf |title=The Weekly Voice |accessdate=17 August 2010}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Film\n|-\n|1980\n|''[[Hum Paanch (1980 film)|Hum Paanch]]''\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[Woh Saat Din]]''\n|-\n|1987\n|''[[Mr. India (1987 film)|Mr. India]]''\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Raat (film)|Raat]]''\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[Drohi (1992 film)|Drohi]]''\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Roop Ki Rani Choron Ka Raja (1993 film)|Roop Ki Rani Choron Ka Raja]]''\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Prem (film)|Prem]]''\n|-\n|1996\n|''[[Loafer (1996 film)|Loafer]]''\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[Judaai (1997 film)|Judaai]]''\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Sirf Tum]]''\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[Pukar (2000 film)|Pukar]]''\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[Hamara Dil Aapke Paas Hai]]''\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Koi Mere Dil Se Poochhe]]''\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Company (film)|Company]]''\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[Shakti (2002 film)|Shakti]]''\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[Khushi (2003 Hindi film)|Khushi]]''\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Run (2004 film)|Run]]''\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Kyun...! Ho Gaya Na]]''\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Bewafaa (2005 film)|Bewafaa]]''\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[No Entry]]''\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Wanted (2009 film)|Wanted]]''\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Milenge Milenge]]''\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Tevar (film)|Tevar]]''\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Mom (film)|Mom]]''\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Nerkonda Paarvai]]'' (Tamil)\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Maidaan]]''\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Valimai]]'' (Tamil)\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Vakeel Saab]]'' (Telugu)\n|-\n|''TBA''\n|''[[Badhaai Ho]] [[remake]]''\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|438470|Boney Kapoor}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kapoor, Boney}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Hindi film producers]]\n", "name_user": "139.167.137.77", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fix birth place)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boney_Kapoor"}
{"title_page": "Yorkshire Coast Line (disambiguation)", "text_new": "The '''[[Yorkshire Coast Line]]''' is a modern term for the Hull to Scarborough railway line.\n\nYorkshire Coast Line can also refer to:\n\n*The coastline of Yorkshire\n**For East Riding of Yorkshire see [[Holderness]] and [[Humber Estuary]], also [[Flamborough Head]] and [[Spurn]]\n**For North Yorkshire see [[North York Moors]], also [[River Tees]]\n*For coastal railway lines in North Yorkshire see\n**[[Scarborough and Whitby Railway]]\n**[[Whitby, Redcar and Middlesbrough Union Railway]]\n*For lines to the coast in the East Riding of Yorkshire see\n**[[Hull and Holderness Railway]]\n**[[Hull and Hornsea Railway]]\n\n{{disambig}}\n", "text_old": "The '''[[Yorkshire Coast Line]]''' is a modern term for the Hull to Scarborough railway line.\n\nYorkshire Coast Line can also refer to:\n\n*The coast line of Yorkshire\n**For East Riding of Yorkshire see [[Holderness]] and [[Humber Estuary]], also [[Flamborough Head]] and [[Spurn]]\n**For North Yorkshire see [[North York Moors]], also [[River Tees]]\n*For coastal railway lines in North Yorkshire see\n**[[Scarborough and Whitby Railway]]\n**[[Whitby, Redcar and Middlesbrough Union Railway]]\n*For lines to the coast in the East Riding of Yorkshire see\n**[[Hull and Holderness Railway]]\n**[[Hull and Hornsea Railway]]\n\n{{disambig}}\n", "name_user": "Mattbuck", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yorkshire_Coast_Line_(disambiguation)"}
{"title_page": "Bolko II of Opole", "text_new": "'''Bolko II<ref>Also named ''Bolko II Henry'' in some sources.</ref> of Opole''' ({{lang-pl|'''Boles\u0142aw II opolski'''}}; before 1300 \u2013 21 June 1356), was a Duke of [[Opole]] from 1313 (with his brother as co-ruler until 1323).\n\nHe was the second son of Duke [[Bolko I of Opole]] by his wife Agnes, probably a daughter of Margrave [[Otto III, Margrave of Brandenburg|Otto III of Brandenburg]].\n\n==Life==\nAt the time of his father's death in 1313, Bolko II and his youngest brother [[Albert of Strzelce|Albert]] inherited the Duchy of Opole as co-rulers; but because at that time both were probably minors, they were placed under the care of their older brother, [[Boles\u0142aw the Elder]]. Bolko II assumed full government over his domains in 1323, and made the formal division of the Duchy with his brother Albert: he received [[Strzelce Opolskie]] and Bolko II retained the main city of Opole.\n\nThanks to his marriage to Elisabeth, daughter of Duke [[Bernard of \u015awidnica]], Bolko II had a temporary close connection with the Polish King [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw I the Elbow-high]] (paternal grandfather of his wife). However, this alliance was short-lived: on 5 April 1327 in [[Wroc\u0142aw]], he paid homage to [[King John of Bohemia]]; he was the last Silesian Duke who became a vassal of Bohemia.\n\nDuring his rule in Opole, Bolko II focused on the economical development of his domains. He introduced German laws (see [[Magdeburg Law]]) in the villages; also, he supported [[trade]] and took care of the state of roads, in order to maintain the safety of travelers.\n\nThe good economy of his Duchy was used by Bolko II to obtain more lands: in 1351 he bought the towns of [[Byczyna]] and [[Kluczbork]] from Duke [[Wenceslaus I of Legnica]] and the district of [[S\u0142awi\u0119cice]] from Duke [[Boles\u0142aw of Bytom]].\n\nBolko II was particularly attached to the [[Franciscan]] monastery of Opole. Inside the monastery, he built the Chapel of St. Anna, which became the Family vault of the Dukes of Opole. When Bolko II died on 21 June 1356, he was buried there.\n\n==Marriage and issue==\nBy 6 May 1326, Bolko II married [[Elisabeth of \u015awidnica|Elisabeth]] (ca. 1315 \u2013 8/9 February 1348), daughter of Duke [[Bernard of \u015awidnica]]. They had seven children:<ref>According to old chronicles, Bolko II remarried after the death of his wife Elisabeth. The name of his second wife was possibly Margareta, and together they had a daughter, called Agnes, later wife of Margrave [[Jobst of Moravia]], later [[King of Germany]]. However, modern historians have debated (and even denied in some cases) the existence of the alleged second wife and daughter of Bolko II. According to the latest researches, this Agnes could be the same as Elisabeth, daughter of W\u0142adys\u0142aw Opolczyk and first (if the existence of Agnes is believed) wife of Jobst. The confusion was in the fact that Elisabeth probably also used the name Agnes (''Elisabeth-Agnes''), a custom which wasn't unusual at that time (for example, Viola of Cieszyn or Richenza of Poland, later Queens of Bohemia, changed their names to Elisabeth after their marriages; see their Wikipedia articles). Sources who supported the existence of one wife of Jobst: {{cite web |last=Marek |first=Miroslav |url=http://genealogy.euweb.cz/piast/piast8.html#EWO |title=Genealogy of the House of Piast |publisher=Genealogy.EU }}{{Self-published source|date=August 2012}};{{Better source|date=August 2012}} sources who supported the existence of two wives of Jobst: [http://wwperson.informatik.uni-erlangen.de/cgi-bin/l3/LANG=engl/F=Jobst Genealogical database by Herbert Stoyan]{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, {{MLCC |warning=1 |url=http://fmg.ac/Projects/MedLands/MORAVIA.htm#Jodokdied1411 |title-date= |title= MORAVIA|date=August 2012}}.</ref>\n#[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Opolczyk]] (c. 1332 \u2013 18 May 1401).\n#[[Bolko III of Strzelce|Bolko III]] (c. 1337 \u2013 21 October 1382).\n#[[Henry of Opole|Henry]] (before 18 August 1338 \u2013 before 23 October 1365).\n#Kunigunde (1340 \u2013 after 4 July 1372), a nun at St. Klara in [[Hungary]] (Alt-Buda).\n#Agnes (c. 1341? \u2013 after 1 June 1390), wife of [[Jobst of Moravia]], and nun at [[Stary S\u0105cz]].\n#Elisabeth (c. 1342/47? \u2013 after 25 April 1382), a nun at [[Trzebnica]].\n#Anna (c. 1348? \u2013 after 12 March 1411), a nun at St. Klara at [[Wroc\u0142aw]].\n\nBolko married a second time to a woman whose name is not recorded.  The result of his union was a daughter:\n* Agnes, who married [[Jobst of Moravia]].\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n*[http://www.poczet.com/opolscy.htm Genealogy of the House of Opole]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-hou|[[House of Piast]]||before 1300|21 June|1356}}\n{{s-reg}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Bolko I of Opole|Bolko I]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Dukes of Silesia|Duke of Opole]]<br/> ''with Albert<br/> (until 1323)''|years=1313\u20131356}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Opolczyk]]<br/> [[Bolko III of Strzelce|Bolko III]]<br/> [[Henry of Opole|Henry]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bolko 02 of Opole}}\n[[Category:13th-century births]]\n[[Category:1356 deaths]]\n[[Category:Piast dynasty]]\n", "text_old": "'''Bolko II<ref>Also named ''Bolko II Henry'' in some sources.</ref> of Opole''' ({{lang-pl|'''Boles\u0142aw II opolski'''}}; before 1300 \u2013 21 June 1356), was a Duke of [[Opole]] from 1313 (with his brother as co-ruler until 1323).\n\nHe was the second son of Duke [[Bolko I of Opole]] by his wife Agnes, probably a daughter of Margrave [[Otto III, Margrave of Brandenburg|Otto III of Brandenburg]].\n\n==Life==\nAt the time of his father's death in 1313, Bolko II and his youngest brother [[Albert of Strzelce|Albert]] inherited the Duchy of Opole as co-rulers; but because at that time both were probably minors, they were placed under the care of their older brother